@flexiarg enrichment/churn-as-signal
@title Git Churn as Behavioral Signal
@sigils [日/示]
@keywords churn, git, hotspot, behavioral, signal, frequency, coupling, temporal
@audience futon developers, enrichment operators
@tone analytic-neutral
@factor Keen investigation (dhammavicaya)
@references [agent/evidence-over-assertion realtime/learn-as-you-go enrichment/ARGUMENT]

! conclusion:
  Ingest raw git commit counts per file as a behavioral complement to
  structural complexity, keeping them separate so they compose freely.

  + context: Tornhill's "Code as a Crime Scene" showed that files which change
    frequently AND are complex are "hotspots" — likely sources of bugs. Files
    that always change together have "temporal coupling" — hidden dependencies.
    Giugliano demonstrated this at multi-million-line scale from Emacs.
  + IF:
    We want to identify hotspots (high risk), temporal coupling (hidden deps),
    and knowledge concentration ("who knows this file?").
  + HOWEVER:
    Git history is noisy — formatting commits, mass renames, and merge commits
    inflate change counts without indicating real complexity growth.
  + THEN:
    Ingest raw commit counts as code/file-churn hyperedges (commits-all-time,
    commits-last-90d, last-touch). Store behavioral and structural signals
    separately so downstream analysis can compose them (churn x complexity =
    hotspot) or filter noise (exclude merge commits) without re-ingesting.
  + BECAUSE:
    Behavioral signals (what DID change) complement structural signals (what
    IS complex). A file with high complexity but zero churn is stable. A file
    with low complexity but high churn is volatile. Neither signal alone
    identifies the hotspot — only their composition does.
  + NEXT-STEPS:
    - evidence: hotspot ranking (top 10 files by churn x complexity)
    - evidence: temporal coupling pairs (files that change together > 5 times)
    - falsifying-observation: if top hotspots are all test files or configs,
      the metric is capturing noise not signal — recalibrate.
